1- We need to add the --dialect option to alfe when we use --clautolisp.

alfe --clautolisp --dialect strict|…|lax …
alfe --bricscad                          …
alfe --autocad                           …

By default --clautolisp uses the strict dialect, but sometimes we want something else.
When --bricscad or --autocad, then --dialect is ignored.

2- add a --list-dialects option to clautolisp and alfe.

--list-dialects  All the possible dialects passed to --dialect option are given:

     strict
     autocad-2022
     autocad-2026
     autocad
     bricscad-v25
     bricscad-v26
     bricscad
     clautolisp
     lax

Without a version, a dialect maps to the last known version.
Always put strict first, and lax last.

for dialect in $(clautolisp --list-dialects) ; do
   clautolisp --dialect $dialect -l test.lsp -q
done


4- warnings should not be errors. This might be corrected by deferred-clautolisp-out-of-dialect-warnings.issue

$ clautolisp
alref.lsp 1.0.1 loaded. (alref-set-root "…") to point at the install root.
clautolisp 1.2.23 — REPL (STRICT dialect, mock-host host) — Ctrl-D to exit.
_$ ((lambda (s) (terpri s) (princ "Expected") (princ "Expected" s) (princ s) (close s))  (open "/tmp/foo" "a"))
clautolisp: runtime error: WRONG-NUMBER-OF-ARGUMENTS: TERPRI takes no arguments in the strict dialect: `(terpri <file>)' is a clautolisp extension (AutoCAD 2026 and BricsCAD V26 document TERPRI as command-line-only). Use (princ "\n" <file>) for a portable file newline, or run under --dialect clautolisp.
AutoLISP backtrace (most recent call first, 4 frames):
  in SUBR TERPRI: (#<file /tmp/foo>)
  in EVAL: (TERPRI S)
  in USUBR LAMBDA: (#<file /tmp/foo>)
  in EVAL: ((LAMBDA (S) (TERPRI S) (PRINC "Expected") (PRINC "Expected" S) (PRINC S) (CLOSE S)) (OPEN "/tmp/foo" "a"))
_$

dialect problems should be signaled with warnings, not errors.



5- setting *AUTOLISP-DIALECT* should change the dialect
dynamically. The second warning/error should have not occured:

