----------------------------------------------------------------------
RESOLVED 1.2.24 -> closed/  (all points)

1- alfe --dialect under --clautolisp (decoupled backend / dialect).
   alfe's --clautolisp/--autocad/--bricscad now set ONLY the backend.
   New EFFECTIVE-DIALECT (cli.lisp) resolves the dialect: a CAD backend
   imposes its own dialect and IGNORES --dialect; the clautolisp backend
   honours --dialect (any order) defaulting to strict. The backend's
   resolve-clautolisp-dialect no longer collapses :clautolisp -> strict,
   so `alfe --clautolisp --dialect clautolisp` now actually enables the
   clautolisp dialect. Verified: `--clautolisp` warns (strict default),
   `--clautolisp --dialect clautolisp` and `--dialect lax --clautolisp`
   are silent (order-independent). The standalone clautolisp binary's
   --clautolisp (= clautolisp dialect) is unchanged.

2- --list-dialects on clautolisp AND alfe (shared CLI option) prints,
   one per line, in canonical order: strict, autocad-2022, autocad-2026,
   autocad, bricscad-v25, bricscad-v26, bricscad, clautolisp, lax
   (strict first, lax last). New reader registry entries: autocad-2022
   (legacy ISO-8859-1 default, pre-UTF-8), bricscad-v25 (== v26 for now),
   and the unversioned aliases autocad -> autocad-2026, bricscad ->
   bricscad-v26. --dialect now accepts all of these (parse-dialect /
   keyword->dialect / resolve-clautolisp-dialect all delegate to the
   reader's single-source-of-truth find-autolisp-dialect).

4- Dialect problems are now WARNINGS, not errors. builtin-terpri under a
   non-clautolisp dialect emits a non-fatal [terpri-file-extension]
   warning (was WRONG-NUMBER-OF-ARGUMENTS) and still writes the newline,
   mirroring the lambda-list-extension convention. The broad sweep of
   any remaining hard dialect errors stays tracked in
   deferred-clautolisp-out-of-dialect-warnings.issue.

5- Setting *AUTOLISP-DIALECT* changes the dialect dynamically.
   current-evaluation-dialect now consults the *AUTOLISP-DIALECT*
   AutoLISP variable first (when it names a known dialect), over the
   session dialect, over strict. So `(setq *AUTOLISP-DIALECT* 'lax)`
   silences the warning from then on. Verified at the REPL/-x.

Tests: builtins-core 1325/1325 (terpri test rewritten to warn+proceed),
reader 114/114, runtime 336/336, alfe conformance 31/31 + spec-coverage
28/28, corpus no new failures (terpri-with-file corpus test -> SKIP,
intentional divergence). Spec: TERPRI extension subsection updated to
warn-not-error; --list-dialects / --dialect usage updated in both CLIs.
